<Layout title="Orthopedic & Musculoskeletal Assessment Tools" description="Orthopedic and musculoskeletal assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Orthopedic &amp; Musculoskeletal</div>
  <h1>Orthopedic &amp; Musculoskeletal Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Clinical decision rules, fracture risk tools, and outcome measures for orthopedic and musculoskeletal nursing care.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ottawa Ankle Rules</strong> — Evidence-based clinical decision tool to determine need for ankle/foot X-ray after injury; sensitivity near 100% for fractures when bone tenderness at specific anatomical points.</li>
      <li><strong>Ottawa Knee Rules</strong> — Clinical criteria for knee radiography after blunt trauma: age ≥55, isolated patella tenderness, fibular head tenderness, inability to flex to 90°, inability to bear weight.</li>
      <li><strong>Pittsburgh Knee Rules</strong> — Knee X-ray decision rule: age &lt;12 or &gt;50, blunt trauma mechanism, inability to bear weight. Simpler than Ottawa Knee Rules with high sensitivity.</li>
      <li><strong>NEXUS Criteria</strong> — Cervical spine clearance without imaging: no posterior midline cervical tenderness, no focal neurological deficit, normal alertness, no intoxication, no painful distracting injury.</li>
      <li><strong>Canadian C-Spine Rule</strong> — Three-step decision rule for C-spine imaging: high-risk factors, low-risk factors allowing range-of-motion testing, and ability to rotate neck 45°.</li>
      <li><strong>FRAX Score</strong> — WHO fracture risk assessment tool: 10-year probability of major osteoporotic fracture and hip fracture using BMD, age, sex, and clinical risk factors. Guides bisphosphonate therapy decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>Harris Hip Score</strong> — Hip arthroplasty outcome measure: pain, function, deformity, and range of motion. Score 90–100 excellent; 80–89 good; 70–79 fair; &lt;70 poor.</li>
      <li><strong>Oxford Knee Score</strong> — 12-item patient-reported outcome for knee arthroplasty. Score 0–48; higher scores indicate better outcomes.</li>
      <li><strong>WOMAC (Western Ontario and McMaster Universities Arthritis Index)</strong> — Osteoarthritis severity: pain, stiffness, and physical function subscales. Widely used in clinical trials for hip and knee OA.</li>
      <li><strong>DVT Prophylaxis Risk Assessment</strong> — Institutional Caprini or similar risk scoring systems guiding VTE prophylaxis selection: mechanical vs. pharmacologic prophylaxis based on bleeding and clot risk balance.</li>
      <li><strong>Compartment Syndrome Assessment</strong> — Clinical evaluation of acute compartment syndrome: the 5 P's plus compartment pressure measurement (&gt;30 mmHg or within 30 mmHg of diastolic pressure indicates fasciotomy).</li>
      <li><strong>Neurovascular Check (5 P's)</strong> — Systematic distal limb assessment: Pain (disproportionate), Pallor, Pulselessness, Paresthesia, Paralysis. Critical for detecting vascular compromise post-fracture or cast application.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
